27. C‘entm-iae tres equitum. These centuries were named after the three original tribes of whom Livy, as already remarked, says nothing. The appellations of Ramnenses and Titienses are adjectives derived respectis-ely from Ramnes and T ities. The third century of equites ought in strictness to have been called Luc-eremas, this being the ad- jective formed from Luceres. The derivation of this last-mentioned term is quite uncertain. We may be very sure, however, that it does not come, as some suppose, from lucus, “ the grove or asylum. ’⁹ The root, probably, is to be found in the Etrurian word Lucumo, and they were, in all likelihood, the followers of the Lucumo Caeles Vibenna wh0, according to one account, joined Romulus with a powerful force against the Sabinea
